{
  "plan_analysis": "The question hinges on whether, within the next 56 days, the Bureau of Industry and Security (BIS) will move an already-in-process or new semiconductor-related export-control package to \u201cfinal rule\u201d status in the Federal Register.  \nWhat we already have: only the formal resolution source (BIS page on Federal Register).  \nKey information gaps a forecaster still needs:\n\n1. Current rulemaking pipeline  \n   \u2022 Are there semiconductor export-control items sitting in \u201cproposed\u201d or \u201cinterim final\u201d status that could be finalized quickly?  \n   \u2022 Has BIS or Commerce conveyed a target publication date?\n\n2. Historical/base-rate context  \n   \u2022 How often has BIS published semiconductor-focused final rules and what is the typical lag from proposal/interim to finalization?  \n   \u2022 Frequency of BIS final rules in comparable 1\u20132-month windows.\n\n3. Background conditions & drivers  \n   \u2022 Political/strategic pressure (Congress, White House, geopolitical tensions) to tighten controls.  \n   \u2022 Industry or allied-government pushback that could delay or water down rules.\n\n4. Contrarian evidence  \n   \u2022 Signals of delay: litigation risk, inter-agency disagreements, supply-chain concerns, or Administration pause.\n\nThe search strategy therefore:  \n\u2022 Mine the Federal Register and BIS sites for the rulemaking docket history to establish the base rate and locate any ready-to-be-finalized rules.  \n\u2022 Scan recent news, statements, and policy documents (regulatory agendas, press briefings, congressional hearings) for timing clues and political momentum.  \n\u2022 Look for reports of obstacles or deliberate slow-rolling that would argue against publication before 1 May 2026.",
